'''Lachlan Ryan Bayliss''' (born 24 July 2002) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who most recently played as a [[central midfielder]] for [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]]. Born in Australia, he represents the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

==Club career==
Bayliss' formative years as a footballer were spent in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Northern Territory]], spending 4 years playing at youth level for [[Mindil Aces FC|Mindil Aces]], before joining the youth set up at [[Central Coast Mariners]] as a 16 year old in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntnews.com.au/sport/football/aleague-clubs-to-play-two-exciting-australia-cup-matches-in-darwin/news-story/89c16260cb9dae06121c8aeda007828c|title=Ex-Darwin soccer junior turned A-League pro to play in Aus Cup|website=NT News|date=14 July 2023}}</ref>

===Central Coast Mariners===
Having come through the age groups for the [[Central Coast Mariners Academy]], Bayliss was promoted into the NPL First Grade team for the Mariners for the 2022 season, with the Mariners competing in the newly renamed [[2022 Football NSW season#2022 NSW League One|NSW League One]] competition, the second tier in the [[National Premier Leagues NSW]] system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://footballnsw.com.au/2022/05/11/lachie-bayliss-enjoying-his-mariners-experience/|title=Lachie Bayliss enjoying his Mariners experience|website=footballnsw.com.au|date=11 May 2022}}</ref> Bayliss made an immediate impact for the team, ending the season as the equal top scorer in the competition with 13 goals in 22 appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/NSW/Scorers2.html|title=New South Wales League One Golden Boot Winners|website=ozfootball.net|author=Greg Stock}}</ref> The season saw the team win the Premiership for finishing top of the table and achieve promotion to the top flight,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ccmariners.com.au/news/academy-mens-first-grade-and-u20s-claim-league-one-premiership-and-club-championship|title=Academy Men's First Grade and U20s claim League One premiership and Club Championship|website=[[Central Coast Mariners FC]]|date=8 August 2022}}</ref> however losing the Grand Final 2–1 after extra time to [[St George City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://footballnsw.com.au/2022/09/03/st-george-city-crowned-2022-league-one-champions/|title=St George City crowned 2022 League One champions|website=footballnsw.com.au|date=3 September 2022}}</ref>

In January 2023, Bayliss was signed on a scholarship contract with the Mariners, joining his older brother [[James Bayliss|James]] in training with the Mariners first team squad for the [[2022-23 A-League Men|2022–23 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ccmariners.com.au/news/kuzevskis-scholarship-extended-bayliss-and-hong-secure-new-scholarships%EF%BF%BC|title=Kuzevski's scholarship extended, Bayliss and Hong secure new scholarships|website=[[Central Coast Mariners FC]]|date=18 January 2023}}</ref> Bayliss continued his fine form into the [[2023 National Premier Leagues NSW|2023 NPL season]], with the team now competing in the top flight following the previous season's promotion. Bayliss was a key member of the team, scoring 9 goals in 21 appearances. Bayliss had a standout performance against [[North West Sydney Spirit FC|North West Sydney Spirit]] at Pluim Park, being involved in all 4 goals for the side in a 4–2 victory, initially with two assists and then scoring two goals in two minutes late in the match to secure the victory from a position of 2–2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mens.nplnsw.com.au/2023/06/18/bayliss-dominates-for-mariners-in-4-2-win-over-spirit/|title=Bayliss dominated for Mariners in 4–2 win over Spirit|website=mens.nplnsw.com.au|date=18 June 2023}}</ref> However, that match would be his penultimate appearance for the club, appearing one final time against [[Sydney FC Youth]]. Bayliss scored again in his farewell match, and was clapped off by teammates and supporters at the end of the match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mens.nplnsw.com.au/2023/06/25/mariners-win-their-fifth-in-a-row-at-home-with-victory-over-sydney-fc/|title=Mariners win their fifth in a row at home with victory over Sydney FC|website=mens.nplnsw.com.au|date=25 June 2023}}</ref>

His departure from the club was confirmed the following day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ccmariners.com.au/news/lachlan-bayliss-departs-central-coast-mariners|title=Lachlan Bayliss departs Central Coast Mariners|website=[[Central Coast Mariners FC]]|date=26 June 2023}}</ref>

===Newcastle Jets===
Following his surprise release from the Mariners, it was announced the following day that Bayliss had signed for [[F3 Derby]] rivals, [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newcastlejetsfc.com.au/news/newcastle-jets-sign-lachlan-bayliss-and-daniel-stynes|title=Newcastle Jets sign Lachlan Bayliss and Daniel Stynes|website=[[Newcastle Jets FC]]|date=27 July 2023}}</ref>

On 17 July 2023, Bayliss made his professional debut in an [[Australia Cup]] play-off match against [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] at [[Darwin Football Stadium|Larrakia Park]] in Darwin, coming off the bench as Newcastle won on penalties to qualify for the [[2023 Australia Cup]] round of 32.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aleaguestats.com/A-League_27MatchDetails_3011.html|title=Newcastle Jets 2–2 Melbourne Victory (Penalties: 4–2) (Cup)|website=aleaguestats.com|date=17 July 2023}}</ref> Bayliss also made his [[A-League Men|A-League]] debut in Newcastle's opening match of the season, a 2–2 away draw against [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]]. Newcastle Jets would announce on 24 June 2024, Bayliss had signed a contract extension for 2 more years.<ref>{{Cite web |last=toml |date=2024-06-24 |title=Lachlan Bayliss Re-Signs |url=https://newcastlejetsfc.com.au/news/lachlan-bayliss-re-signs/ |access-date=2024-06-24 |website=Newcastle Jets |language=en-AU}}</ref>

Bayliss scored his first professional goal in round eight of the [[2024–25 A-League Men|2024–25 A-League]] in a 4–0 win over [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lachlan Bayliss {{!}} Isuzu UTE Goal of the Week Winner {{!}} Round 8 |url=https://newcastlejetsfc.com.au/videos/id/lachlan-bayliss-isuzu-ute-goal-of-the-week-winner-round-8/6366215629112/ |access-date=2026-03-27 |website=Newcastle Jets |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=toml |date=2024-12-14 |title=Dominant Jets put four past Perth Glory |url=https://newcastlejetsfc.com.au/news/dominant-jets-put-four-past-perth-glory/ |access-date=2026-03-27 |website=Newcastle Jets |language=en-AU}}</ref> Bayliss featured in all 26 league matches, starting 19 of them.

Bayliss contributed to Newcastle Jets’ second major trophy, making four appearances during their victorious [[2025 Australia Cup]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-10-04 |title=Newcastle Jets win Hahn Australia Cup 2025 with 3-1 victory over Heidelberg United {{!}} Australia Cup |url=https://australiacup.com.au/news/newcastle-jets-win-hahn-australia-cup-2025-3-1-victory-over-heidelberg-united |access-date=2026-03-27 |website=australiacup.com.au |language=en}}</ref> Bayliss and the Jets would go on to win their second title of the season, winning the A-League Men [[A-League Men#Trophy and Plate|Premier's Plate]] on 19 April 2026 following [[Auckland FC|Auckland FC's]] 1–0 loss to the [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/aleague-men-newcastle-jets-win-second-trophy-of-the-season-with-premiership-triumph/|title=Newcastle Jets win second trophy of the season with Premiership triumph|first=James|last=Dodd|website=[[A-Leagues]]|date=19 April 2026|access-date=20 April 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/48529247/ccm-upset-auckland-hand-newcastle-jets-aleague-premiership|title=CCM upset Auckland to hand Newcastle Jets A-League premiership|date=19 April 2026|access-date=20 April 2026|website=[[ESPN Australia]]}}</ref> Bayliss scored 5 goals and registered 3 assists during the regular season.<ref name="ultimatealeague.com">{{Cite web |title=Lachlan Bayliss (Midfielder, Newcastle Jets) : |url=https://www.ultimatealeague.com/player/?player_id=1642 |access-date=2026-04-28 |website=Ultimate A-League |language=en}}</ref>

On 28 May 2026, the club confirmed that Bayliss would depart the club at the expiration of his contract at the end of the [[2025–26 A-League Men|2025–26 season]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2026-05-28 |title=Newcastle Jets Confirm A-League Men's Departures |url=https://newcastlejetsfc.com.au/news/newcastle-jets-confirm-a-league-mens-departures-25-26/ |access-date=2026-05-28 |website=Newcastle Jets |language=en-AU}}</ref>

==International career==
Bayliss is eligible to represent both [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] and [[New Zealand men's national soccer team|New Zealand]], through his father being born in New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web |title='Emotional' Stamenić on leading All Whites after dad's passing |url=https://www.1news.co.nz/2026/03/31/emotional-stamenic-on-leading-all-whites-after-dads-passing/ |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=1News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2026-02-10 |title=Lachlan Bayliss earns January nomination for A-League Young Player award |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2026/02/10/lachlan-bayliss-earns-january-nomination-for-a-league-young-player-award/ |access-date=2026-04-25 |website=Friends of Football |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

In August 2023, Bayliss was called up to [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|New Zealand U23]] squad for [[2023 OFC Men's Olympic Qualifying Tournament|OFC Olympic qualification]] matches against [[Papua New Guinea national under-23 soccer team|Papua New Guinea]] and [[Fiji national under-23 football team|Fiji]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newcastlejetsfc.com.au/news/jets-duo-called-up-for-australia-and-new-zealand-u23s|title=Jets duo called up for Australia and New Zealand U23's|website=[[Newcastle Jets FC]]|date=17 August 2023}}</ref> In July 2024, he was named as an alternate player for the [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|New Zealand Olympic football team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's Football Team Announced for Paris 2024|url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/143021?newsfeedId=1275608|access-date=14 July 2024|work=[[New Zealand Football]]|language=en}}</ref> On 23 July 2024, Bayliss was announced as being included in the squad proper after [[Riley Bidois]] withdrew due to injury<ref>{{cite news |title=New Zealand forced to make squad changes ahead of Olympic Games opener|url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2024/07/23/new-zealand-forced-to-make-squad-changes-ahead-of-olympic-games-opener/ |publisher=Friends Of Football |date=23 July 2024}}</ref> and he subsequently appeared in all three of New Zealand’s matches.

On 16 March 2026, Bayliss earned his maiden call-up to the [[New Zealand men's national football team|All Whites]] for the [[FIFA Series]], where the team were scheduled to face [[Finland national football team|Finland]] and [[Chile national football team|Chile]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Debut Call-Up for Newcastle Jets' Lachlan Bayliss in All Whites Squad for Home Games Against Finland and Chile This March |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2026-03-15 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Voerman |first=Andrew |title=Newcastle Jets star Lachlan Bayliss gets chance to press FIFA World Cup case with All Whites |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360949567/newcastle-jets-star-lachlan-bayliss-gets-chance-press-fifa-world-cup-case-all-whites |access-date=2026-03-15 |website=www.stuff.co.nz}}</ref> Bayliss made his debut in a 0–2 loss to Finland.<ref>{{Cite web |title=All Whites fail to fire in 2-0 loss to Finland in Auckland |url=https://www.1news.co.nz/2026/03/27/all-whites-fail-to-fire-in-2-0-loss-to-finland-in-auckland/ |access-date=2026-03-27 |website=1News |language=en}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Bayliss' brother [[James Bayliss|James]] also played for the Central Coast Mariners, making 13 A-League appearances and currently played for [[Auckland FC|Auckland FC OFC PL team]]. The brothers featured together in the Mariners NPL first grade sides in 2022 and 2023.{{citation needed|date=January 2024}} They are not related to three-time [[Superbike World Championship|Superbike World Champion]] [[Troy Bayliss]].

